{"title_page": "Kazusa Takashima", "text_new": "{{nihongo|'''Kazusa Takashima'''|\u9ad8\u5d8b \u4e0a\u7dcf|Takashima Kazusa|born October 23 in [[Hokkaido]]}} is a Japanese [[Mangaka|manga artist]], famous for her [[yaoi]] [[manga]]. After being a [[doujinshi]] artist from 1999\u20132000, she became an official manga artist in 2001. In addition to this, she has also illustrated a number of [[light novels]].\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Hokkaido]] on October 23, she began her career in 1999 as a [[Houshin Engi]] [[doujinshi]] artist as well as doing fanart from popular series like [[Hikaru no Go]], [[Shaman King]] and [[Yami no Matsuei]]. Her works were predominantly [[yaoi|BL]]-related.\n\nFinally she got her break when her first original series, [[Harlem Beat wa Yoake Made]] was serialized in [[Kadokawa Shoten|Kadokawa]]'s [[Monthly Asuka]]. After a well received debut, the company decided to publish the series into an actual volume.<ref>[http://www.kadokawa.co.jp/comic/bk_detail.php?pcd=200203000671 Kadokawa: Harlem Beat wa Yoake Made]</ref> After that, she went on to make another of her well-known series: [[Last Client]] which was serialized in [[Libre Publishing|Biblos]]'s ''BexBoy Magazine'' in 2002. In that same year she got [[Wild Rock]] published by [[Libre Publishing|Biblos]] (it went straight to manga form; not serialized). Since then she has published roughly nine distinctive titles through various publishing companies and has been the illustrator of a number of [[light novels]] by various authors, and other media.\n\nShe filed a lawsuit against [[Kayono]] in 2004. The lawsuit was founded on Takashima's belief that Kayono had directly traced over her work ''[[Wild Rock]]'', and used it for her own [[manga]].<ref>[http://kayono_kenshou.at.infoseek.co.jp/kenshougazou.html Kayono Kenshou] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100526074907/http://kayono_kenshou.at.infoseek.co.jp/kenshougazou.html |date=2010-05-26 }}</ref> The judge threw out the case (resulting in Takashima losing). Takashima decided to go on hiatus, leaving all of her series unfinished. She resumed work in 2007 with the fourth installment of [[Harlem Beat wa Yoake Made]]. Since then, she has finished the series, [[Wild Rock]] and [[Man's Best Friend (manga)|Man's Best Friend]] have been reprinted, and she did a [[centerfold|pinup]] of Chris (from her series [[Last Client]], which had been left on hiatus) in [[Libre Publishing|Biblos]]'s ''GOLD magazine''. She also changed websites.\n\nTakashima was more active on her [[blog]] in 2011,<ref>[http://kazusa-t.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/archives.html maxmaximum: Archives] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708174044/http://kazusa-t.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/archives.html |date=2011-07-08 }}</ref> and in her December 10 entry, stated that she \"took a break\" that she felt was necessary and that she \"plans to work hard\" in the new year.<ref>[http://kazusa-t.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2009/12/index.html maxmaximum: December 10th Entry] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100205033331/http://kazusa-t.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2009/12/index.html |date=2010-02-05 }} Then this blog was abandoned.</ref>\n\nIn 2013, she became the illustrator for [[Mirage of Blaze]]'s prequel light novels by Kuwabara Mizuna<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mizuna.info/data/book/9784086017756 |title=Kuwabara Mizuna's Website |access-date=2019-06-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622170234/http://mizuna.info/data/book/9784086017756 |archive-date=2019-06-22 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref>, titled Mirage of Blaze: The Showa Era Chapters. The 11 Volumes finished publication in 2017, though her art was used for the promotional material for the stage play<ref>[https://shop-ep.net/trifle_stage/shopping/a04020102/iid/0000000001449/ Trifle Entertainment's Website] {{webarchive|url=https://shop-ep.net/trifle_stage/shopping/a04020102/iid/0000000001449/ |date=2015-02-28 }}</ref>. This is the longest, single series light novel she's worked on thus far.\n\nIn 2014, she also revitalized her Cocolog Blog, but under a new name.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/ |title=Takashima's Cocolog Blog |access-date=2019-06-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816130920/http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/ |archive-date=2019-08-16 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref> Among the early posts on here, she lists, in great detail, all of her various works, including published manga, illustration contributions, and minor things like doujinshi, pinups, advertisements, one-shot stories, etc. up to the present (2014)<ref>[http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/20002001-3120.html Takashima's Works 2000-2001] {{webarchive|url=http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/20002001-3120.html |date=2014-06-29 }}</ref><ref>[http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/20022006-3932.html Takashima's Works 2002-2006] {{webarchive|url=http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/20022006-3932.html |date=2014-06-29 }}</ref><ref>[http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/2007-edfc.html Takashima's Works 2007] {{webarchive|url=http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/2007-edfc.html |date=2014-06-29 }}</ref><ref>[http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/20082009-6cc1.html Takashima's Works 2008-2009] {{webarchive|url=http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/20082009-6cc1.html |date=2014-06-29 }}</ref><ref>[http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/20102013-655b.html Takashima's Works 2010-2013] {{webarchive|url=http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/20102013-655b.html |date=2014-06-29 }}</ref><ref>[http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/2014-0305.html Takashima's Works 2014] {{webarchive|url=http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/2014-0305.html |date=2014-06-29 }}</ref> and slightly beyond that with publication plans for the following year (2015).<ref>[http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/2015-8914.html Takashima's Works 2015] {{webarchive|url=http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/2015-8914.html |date=2014-06-29 }}</ref> It seems even now she doesn't post regularly to her blog with months passing before a new post appears, but she does post with more regularity to Instagram.\n\nShe started an Instagram account in February 2016 where she posted various updates or notices about minor illustration work she was doing, or fan art and concept art.<ref>[https://www.instagram.com/takashimakazusa/?hl=en Takashima's Instagram] {{webarchive|url=https://www.instagram.com/takashimakazusa/?hl=en |date=2016-02-08 }}</ref> Larger resolution versions of all of the posts can be found on her previously mentioned Cocolog blog. In 2018, she seemed to finally end her hiatus with a new manga titled, [[Hige to Shippo to Kannazuki|Whiskers and Tails with Kannaduki]]<ref>[https://www.instagram.com/p/BfbXYYThoWg/?hl=en Takashima's Instagram] {{webarchive|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BfbXYYThoWg/?hl=en |date=2018-02-20 }}</ref>. It is being serialized in [[Libre Publishing|Biblos]]'s ''BexBoy Gold Magazine''.\n\nIn June 2019, she made a post to her blog advertising the latest chapter of Whiskers and Tails, and mentioned that she'd been considering continuing one of her old works.<ref>[http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2019/06/post-846f0b.html Blog Post from June 2019] {{webarchive|url=http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2019/06/post-846f0b.html |date=2019-06-16 }}</ref> This was exciting news for fans as several of her unfinished works (Last Client, Hakobunjaa, etc.) were very popular before her hiatus and their subsequent discontinuation. She gave no hints about which series she was considering bringing back, but sounded sure she would continue at least one of them.\n\n==Major works==\n* [[Harlem Beat wa Yoake Made]] (2001\u20132008)\n* [[Last Client]] (2002; discontinued in 2004)\n* [[Wild Rock]] (2001\u20132002)\n* [[Dragon X Boy]] (2003; discontinued after 1 chapter.)\n* [[Hakobunjaa|Takuhai Sentai: Hakobunja]] (2003; discontinued after 1 chapter.)\n* [[Private Magician]] (2003; discontinued after 3 chapters.)\n* [[Man's Best Friend (manga)|Kingyo Hime]] (2003\u20132004; extra in Inu mo Arukeba manga.)\n* [[Man's Best Friend (manga)|Inu mo Arukeba: Fallin' Love]] (2004)\n* [[Man's Best Friend (manga)|Mata Natsu ga Kita & Pinpoint Lovers]] (2004; extra in Inu mo Arukeba manga.)\n* [[Mirage of Blaze|Mirage of Blaze: The Showa Era Chapters]] (2014; illustrator)\n* [[Hige to Shippo to Kannazuki|Whiskers and Tails with Kannaduki]] (2018-Present)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080313011415/http://kazusa-t.cocolog-nifty.com/ Old Cocolog Blog]\n* [http://www.kazusa-t.com/ Former Homepage]\n* [http://tk.kisuki.com/ Informative Fanpage]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100504223512/http://community.livejournal.com/maxmaximum_tk Fan Translation of Various Sources of Information]\n* [http://mizuna.info/data/book/9784086017756 Kuwabara Mizuna's Website Listing the Showa Era Chapter Prequels]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/takashimakazusa/?hl=en Takashima's Instagram]\n* [http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2018/04/post-a96f.html New Cocolog Blog]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Takashima, Kazusa}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Manga artists from Hokkaido]]\n[[Category:Japanese cartoonists]]\n", "text_old": "{{nihongo|'''Kazusa Takashima'''|\u9ad8\u5d8b \u4e0a\u7dcf|Takashima Kazusa|born October 23 in [[Hokkaido]]}} is a Japanese [[Mangaka|manga artist]], famous for her [[yaoi]] [[manga]]. After being a [[doujinshi]] artist from 1999\u20132000, she became an official manga artist in 2001. In addition to this, she has also illustrated a number of [[light novels]].\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Hokkaido]] on October 23, she began her career in 1999 as a [[Houshin Engi]] [[doujinshi]] artist as well as doing fanart from popular series like [[Hikaru no Go]], [[Shaman King]] and [[Yami no Matsuei]]. Her works were predominantly [[yaoi|BL]]-related.\n\nFinally she got her break when her first original series, [[Harlem Beat wa Yoake Made]] was serialized in [[Kadokawa Shoten|Kadokawa]]'s [[Monthly Asuka]]. After a well received debut, the company decided to publish the series into an actual volume.<ref>[http://www.kadokawa.co.jp/comic/bk_detail.php?pcd=200203000671 Kadokawa: Harlem Beat wa Yoake Made]</ref> After that, she went on to make another of her well-known series: [[Last Client]] which was serialized in [[Libre Publishing|Biblos]]'s ''BexBoy Magazine'' in 2002. In that same year she got [[Wild Rock]] published by [[Libre Publishing|Biblos]] (it went straight to manga form; not serialized). Since then she has published roughly nine distinctive titles through various publishing companies and has been the illustrator of a number of [[light novels]] by various authors, and other media.\n\nShe filed a lawsuit against [[Kayono]] in 2004. The lawsuit was founded on Takashima's belief that Kayono had directly traced over her work ''[[Wild Rock]]'', and used it for her own [[manga]].<ref>[http://kayono_kenshou.at.infoseek.co.jp/kenshougazou.html Kayono Kenshou] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100526074907/http://kayono_kenshou.at.infoseek.co.jp/kenshougazou.html |date=2010-05-26 }}</ref> The judge threw out the case (resulting in Takashima losing). Takashima decided to go on hiatus, leaving all of her series unfinished. She resumed work in 2007 with the fourth installment of [[Harlem Beat wa Yoake Made]]. Since then, she has finished the series, [[Wild Rock]] and [[Man's Best Friend (manga)|Man's Best Friend]] have been reprinted, and she did a [[centerfold|pinup]] of Chris (from her series [[Last Client]], which had been left on hiatus) in [[Libre Publishing|Biblos]]'s ''GOLD magazine''. She also changed websites.\n\nTakashima was more active on her [[blog]] in 2011,<ref>[http://kazusa-t.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/archives.html maxmaximum: Archives] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708174044/http://kazusa-t.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/archives.html |date=2011-07-08 }}</ref> and in her December 10 entry, stated that she \"took a break\" that she felt was necessary and that she \"plans to work hard\" in the new year.<ref>[http://kazusa-t.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2009/12/index.html maxmaximum: December 10th Entry] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100205033331/http://kazusa-t.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2009/12/index.html |date=2010-02-05 }} Then this blog was abandoned.</ref>\n\nIn 2013, she became the illustrator for [[Mirage of Blaze]]'s prequel light novels by Kuwabara Mizuna<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mizuna.info/data/book/9784086017756 |title=Kuwabara Mizuna's Website |access-date=2019-06-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622170234/http://mizuna.info/data/book/9784086017756 |archive-date=2019-06-22 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref>, titled Mirage of Blaze: The Showa Era Chapters. The 11 Volumes finished publication in 2017, though her art was used for the promotional material for the stage play<ref>[https://shop-ep.net/trifle_stage/shopping/a04020102/iid/0000000001449/ Trifle Entertainment's Website] {{webarchive|url=https://shop-ep.net/trifle_stage/shopping/a04020102/iid/0000000001449/ |date=2015-02-28 }}</ref>. This is the longest, single series light novel she's worked on thus far.\n\nIn 2014, she also revitalized her Cocolog Blog, but under a new name.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/ |title=Takashima's Cocolog Blog |access-date=2019-06-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816130920/http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/ |archive-date=2019-08-16 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref> Among the early posts on here, she lists, in great detail, all of her various works, including published manga, illustration contributions, and minor things like doujinshi, pinups, advertisements, one-shot stories, etc. up to the present (2014)<ref>[http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/20002001-3120.html Takashima's Works 2000-2001] {{webarchive|url=http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/20002001-3120.html |date=2014-06-29 }}</ref><ref>[http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/20022006-3932.html Takashima's Works 2002-2006] {{webarchive|url=http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/20022006-3932.html |date=2014-06-29 }}</ref><ref>[http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/2007-edfc.html Takashima's Works 2007] {{webarchive|url=http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/2007-edfc.html |date=2014-06-29 }}</ref><ref>[http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/20082009-6cc1.html Takashima's Works 2008-2009] {{webarchive|url=http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/20082009-6cc1.html |date=2014-06-29 }}</ref><ref>[http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/20102013-655b.html Takashima's Works 2010-2013] {{webarchive|url=http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/20102013-655b.html |date=2014-06-29 }}</ref><ref>[http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/2014-0305.html Takashima's Works 2014] {{webarchive|url=http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/2014-0305.html |date=2014-06-29 }}</ref> and slightly beyond that with publication plans for the following year (2015).<ref>[http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/2015-8914.html Takashima's Works 2015] {{webarchive|url=http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2014/06/2015-8914.html |date=2014-06-29 }}</ref> It seems even now she doesn't post regularly to her blog with months passing before a new post appears, but she does post with more regularity to Instagram.\n\nShe started an Instagram account in February of 2016 where she posted various updates or notices about minor illustration work she was doing, or fan art and concept art.<ref>[https://www.instagram.com/takashimakazusa/?hl=en Takashima's Instagram] {{webarchive|url=https://www.instagram.com/takashimakazusa/?hl=en |date=2016-02-08 }}</ref> Larger resolution versions of all of the posts can be found on her previously mentioned Cocolog blog. In 2018, she seemed to finally end her hiatus with a new manga titled, [[Hige to Shippo to Kannazuki|Whiskers and Tails with Kannaduki]]<ref>[https://www.instagram.com/p/BfbXYYThoWg/?hl=en Takashima's Instagram] {{webarchive|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BfbXYYThoWg/?hl=en |date=2018-02-20 }}</ref>. It is being serialized in [[Libre Publishing|Biblos]]'s ''BexBoy Gold Magazine''.\n\nIn June of 2019, she made a post to her blog advertising the latest chapter of Whiskers and Tails, and mentioned that she'd been considering continuing one of her old works.<ref>[http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2019/06/post-846f0b.html Blog Post from June 2019] {{webarchive|url=http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2019/06/post-846f0b.html |date=2019-06-16 }}</ref> This was exciting news for fans as several of her unfinished works (Last Client, Hakobunjaa, etc.) were very popular before her hiatus and their subsequent discontinuation. She gave no hints about which series she was considering bringing back, but sounded sure she would continue at least one of them.\n\n==Major Works==\n* [[Harlem Beat wa Yoake Made]] (2001-2008)\n* [[Last Client]] (2002; discontinued in 2004)\n* [[Wild Rock]] (2001-2002)\n* [[Dragon X Boy]] (2003; discontinued after 1 chapter.)\n* [[Hakobunjaa|Takuhai Sentai: Hakobunja]] (2003; discontinued after 1 chapter.)\n* [[Private Magician]] (2003; discontinued after 3 chapters.)\n* [[Man's Best Friend (manga)|Kingyo Hime]] (2003-2004; extra in Inu mo Arukeba manga.)\n* [[Man's Best Friend (manga)|Inu mo Arukeba: Fallin' Love]] (2004)\n* [[Man's Best Friend (manga)|Mata Natsu ga Kita & Pinpoint Lovers]] (2004; extra in Inu mo Arukeba manga.)\n* [[Mirage of Blaze|Mirage of Blaze: The Showa Era Chapters]] (2014; illustrator)\n* [[Hige to Shippo to Kannazuki|Whiskers and Tails with Kannaduki]] (2018-Present)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080313011415/http://kazusa-t.cocolog-nifty.com/ Old Cocolog Blog]\n* [http://www.kazusa-t.com/ Former Homepage]\n* [http://tk.kisuki.com/ Informative Fanpage]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100504223512/http://community.livejournal.com/maxmaximum_tk Fan Translation of Various Sources of Information]\n* [http://mizuna.info/data/book/9784086017756 Kuwabara Mizuna's Website Listing the Showa Era Chapter Prequels]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/takashimakazusa/?hl=en Takashima's Instagram]\n* [http://takashimakazusa.cocolog-nifty.com/blog/2018/04/post-a96f.html New Cocolog Blog]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Takashima, Kazusa}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Manga artists from Hokkaido]]\n[[Category:Japanese cartoonists]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced: 2001-2008 \u2192 2001\u20132008 (3), Works \u2192 works,typo(s) fixed: February of 2016 \u2192 February 2016 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kazusa_Takashima"}
{"title_page": "Breaking the Chains (album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Breaking the Chains\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Dokken]]\n| cover      = Dokken - 1981 - Breakin' the Chains (original).jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = First edition cover art\n| released   = 1981 <small>(Europe)</small><br>September 18, 1983 <small>(US)</small>\n| recorded   = [[Dieter Dierks#Dierks Studios|Dierks Studios]], Cologne, Germany\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]], [[Glam metal]]\n| length     = 35:01 (1981 version)<br>36:24 (1983 version)\n| label      = [[Carrere Records|Carrere]] (1981)<br>[[Elektra Records|Elektra]] (1983)\n| producer   = [[Michael Wagener]], Dokken\n| prev_title = [[Back in the Streets]]\n| prev_year  = 1979\n| next_title = [[Tooth and Nail (Dokken album)|Tooth and Nail]]\n| next_year  = 1984\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Breaking the Chains\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = I Can't See You\" / \"Breaking the Chains\n | single1date = 1981 <small>(Europe only)</small>\n | single2     = Young Girls\" / \"Paris\n | single2date = 1981 <small>(Europe only)</small>\n | single3     = We're Illegal\" / \"Paris\n | single3date = 1982 <small>(Europe only)</small>\n | single4     = [[Breaking the Chains (song)|Breaking the Chains]]\" / \"Felony\n | single4date = 1983\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = studio\n | cover   = Dokken - Breaking the Chains.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = 1983 reissue\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/breaking-the-chains-mw0000189795 |title=Dokken - Breaking the Chains review |last=Gomes |first=Z. |work=[[AllMusic]] |publisher=[[All Media Network]] |accessdate=2015-01-30 }}</ref>\n| rev2 =''[[Martin Popoff|The Collector's Guide to Heavy Metal]]''\n| rev2Score = 7/10<ref name=\"martin\" >{{cite book | last1 = Popoff | first1 = Martin | authorlink1 = Martin Popoff | title = The Collector's Guide to Heavy Metal: Volume 2: The Eighties | publisher = [[Collector's Guide Publishing]] | date = November 1, 2005 | location = [[Burlington, Ontario]], [[Canada]] | isbn = 978-1-894959-31-5}}</ref>\n| noprose = yes\n}}\n\n'''''Breaking the Chains''''' is the debut studio album by [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Dokken]].\nThe album was originally released in 1981 in Europe as '''''Breakin' the Chains''''' on the French label [[Carrere Records]].<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Dokken-Breakin-The-Chains/release/3543727 \"Dokken - Breakin' The Chains\"]. [[Discogs]]. Retrieved 2014-02-25.</ref> This version contains some different mixes and titles of songs from the later US edition. \"Paris Is Burning\" is called \"Paris\" and is actually a studio version as opposed to the live recording in [[Berlin]] from December 1982. The album also contained a song called \"We're Illegal\", which was later turned into \"Live to Rock\".\n\nThe album was remixed, partially re-recorded, renamed and released in the US in 1983 by [[Elektra Records]] and reached number 136 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/breaking-the-chains-mw0000189795/awards |title=Breaking the Chains Billboard Albums |work=[[AllMusic]] |publisher=[[All Media Network]] |accessdate=2015-01-30 }}</ref> The album was considered a flop by the label, which had the intention to drop the band. However, Dokken management convinced Elektra that they could make a more successful album, which materialized in ''[[Tooth and Nail (Dokken album)|Tooth and Nail]]'' in September 1984. ''Breaking the Chains'' title track was named the 62nd greatest hard rock song by [[VH1]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Vh1 Top 100 Hard Rock Songs |publisher=Spreadit Music.org |url=http://music.spreadit.org/vh1-top-100-hard-rock-songs/ |accessdate=February 7, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212180319/http://music.spreadit.org/vh1-top-100-hard-rock-songs/ |archivedate=February 12, 2009 }}</ref> It is featured on the radio station \"V-ROCK\" in the 2006 video game ''[[Grand Theft Auto: Vice City Stories]]''.\n\nIn a discussion with [[George Lynch (musician)|George Lynch]] on January 26, 2011, he mentioned the existence of 500 copies of the Carrere Records ''Breakin' the Chains'' version printed with the Don Dokken moniker, instead of Dokken. This version also featured different album cover art.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://bravewords.com/news/george-lynch-and-don-dokken-trade-barbs-on-dokkens-breaking-the-chains-debut-audio-interviews-streaming |title=GEORGE LYNCH And DON DOKKEN Trade Barbs On DOKKEN's Breaking The Chains Debut; Audio Interviews Streaming |magazine=[[Brave Words & Bloody Knuckles]] |date=5 January 2005 |accessdate=2015-06-29 }}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n\n===1981 Breakin' The Chains (Carrere Records)===\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Side one\n| all_writing     = [[Don Dokken]] and [[George Lynch (musician)|George Lynch]], except where noted\n| title1          = [[Breaking the Chains (song)|Breaking the Chains]]\n| length1         = 3:43\n| title2          = Seven Thunders\n| note2         = Dokken, Lynch, [[Mick Brown (musician)|Mick Brown]]\n| length2         = 3:56\n| title3          = I Can't See You\n| note3         = Dokken, [[Juan Croucier]]\n| length3         = 3:12\n| title4          = In the Middle\n| length4         = 3:44\n| title5          = We're Illegal\n| note5         = Dokken, Lynch, Croucier\n| length5         = 3:39\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Side two\n| title6          = Paris \n| length6         = 3:46\n| title7          = Stick to Your Guns\n| length7         = 3:25\n| title8          = Young Girls\n| length8         = 3:14\n| title9          = Felony\n| length9         = 3:25\n| title10         = Nightrider\n| note10        = Dokken, Lynch, Brown\n| length10        = 3:14\n| total_length    = 35:01\n}}\n\n===1983 Breaking The Chains (Elektra Records)===\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Side one\n| title1          = Breaking the Chains\n| length1         = 3:43\n| title2          = In the Middle\n| length2         = 3:43\n| title3          = Felony\n| length3         = 3:08\n| title4          = I Can't See You\n| note4         = Dokken, [[Juan Croucier]]\n| length4         = 3:12\n| title5          = Live to Rock (Rock to Live)\n| note5         = Dokken, Lynch, Croucier\n| length5         = 3:39\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Side two\n| title6          = Nightrider\n| note6         = Dokken, Lynch, [[Mick Brown (musician)|Mick Brown]]\n| length6         = 3:13\n| title7          = Seven Thunders\n| note7         = Dokken, Lynch, Brown\n| length7         = 3:55\n| title8          = Young Girls\n| length8         = 3:14\n| title9          = Stick to Your Guns\n| length9         = 3:25\n| title10         = Paris Is Burning\n| note10          = live in Berlin, December 1982\n| length10        = 5:07\n| total_length    = 36:24\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n\n===Band members===\n===1981 Breakin' The Chains (Carrere Records)===\n*[[Don Dokken]] \u2013 [[lead vocalist|lead vocals]], [[rhythm guitar]], lead guitar\n*[[George Lynch (musician)|George Lynch]] \u2013 [[lead guitar]]\n*[[Mick Brown (musician)|\"Wild\" Mick Brown]] \u2013 [[drum kit|drums]]\n*[[Juan Croucier]] \u2013 [[bassline|bass]], [[backing vocalist|background vocals, co-lead vocals on 'We're Illegal']]\n\n===1983 Breaking The Chains (Elektra Records)===\n*[[Don Dokken]] \u2013 [[lead vocalist|lead vocals]], [[rhythm guitar]], lead guitar\n*[[George Lynch (musician)|George Lynch]] \u2013 [[lead guitar]]\n*[[Mick Brown (musician)|\"Wild\" Mick Brown]] \u2013 [[drum kit|drums]]\n*[[Juan Croucier]] \u2013 [[bassline|bass]], [[backing vocalist|background vocals]]\n\n===Additional Musicians===\n*[[Peter Baltes]] - bass (only on 1981 version)\n*[[Tom Croucier]] - bass (only on 1981 version)\n\n===Production===\n*[[Michael Wagener]] \u2013 [[record producer|production]], [[audio engineer|engineering]], [[mixing engineer|mixing]]\n*Wyn Davis \u2013 mixing\n*[[Joe Gastwirt]] \u2013 [[mastering engineer|mastering]]\n\n==Notes==\n\nOn the original ''Breakin' The Chains'' Carrere version, released as Don Dokken, several song titles are misspelled on the back cover.  Namely \"I Can't See You\" (\"I Can See You\"), \"Stick To Your Guns\" (\"Still To Your Guns\"), and \"Young Girls\" (\"Young Girl\"). On the French Carrere vinyl release, the songs are spelled correctly, but Lynch's name is misspelled as \u201cGeorges Lynch\u201d.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Dokken}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Breaking The Chains (Dokken Album)}}\n[[Category:1981 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Michael Wagener]]\n[[Category:Dokken albums]]\n[[Category:Elektra Records albums]]\n[[Category:Carrere Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Breaking the Chains\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Dokken]]\n| cover      = Dokken - 1981 - Breakin' the Chains (original).jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = First edition cover art\n| released   = 1981 <small>(Europe)</small><br>September 18, 1983 <small>(US)</small>\n| recorded   = [[Dieter Dierks#Dierks Studios|Dierks Studios]], Cologne, Germany\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]], [[hard rock]]\n| length     = 35:01 (1981 version)<br>36:24 (1983 version)\n| label      = [[Carrere Records|Carrere]] (1981)<br>[[Elektra Records|Elektra]] (1983)\n| producer   = [[Michael Wagener]], Dokken\n| prev_title = [[Back in the Streets]]\n| prev_year  = 1979\n| next_title = [[Tooth and Nail (Dokken album)|Tooth and Nail]]\n| next_year  = 1984\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Breaking the Chains\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = I Can't See You\" / \"Breaking the Chains\n | single1date = 1981 <small>(Europe only)</small>\n | single2     = Young Girls\" / \"Paris\n | single2date = 1981 <small>(Europe only)</small>\n | single3     = We're Illegal\" / \"Paris\n | single3date = 1982 <small>(Europe only)</small>\n | single4     = [[Breaking the Chains (song)|Breaking the Chains]]\" / \"Felony\n | single4date = 1983\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = studio\n | cover   = Dokken - Breaking the Chains.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = 1983 reissue\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/breaking-the-chains-mw0000189795 |title=Dokken - Breaking the Chains review |last=Gomes |first=Z. |work=[[AllMusic]] |publisher=[[All Media Network]] |accessdate=2015-01-30 }}</ref>\n| rev2 =''[[Martin Popoff|The Collector's Guide to Heavy Metal]]''\n| rev2Score = 7/10<ref name=\"martin\" >{{cite book | last1 = Popoff | first1 = Martin | authorlink1 = Martin Popoff | title = The Collector's Guide to Heavy Metal: Volume 2: The Eighties | publisher = [[Collector's Guide Publishing]] | date = November 1, 2005 | location = [[Burlington, Ontario]], [[Canada]] | isbn = 978-1-894959-31-5}}</ref>\n| noprose = yes\n}}\n\n'''''Breaking the Chains''''' is the debut studio album by [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Dokken]].\nThe album was originally released in 1981 in Europe as '''''Breakin' the Chains''''' on the French label [[Carrere Records]].<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Dokken-Breakin-The-Chains/release/3543727 \"Dokken - Breakin' The Chains\"]. [[Discogs]]. Retrieved 2014-02-25.</ref> This version contains some different mixes and titles of songs from the later US edition. \"Paris Is Burning\" is called \"Paris\" and is actually a studio version as opposed to the live recording in [[Berlin]] from December 1982. The album also contained a song called \"We're Illegal\", which was later turned into \"Live to Rock\".\n\nThe album was remixed, partially re-recorded, renamed and released in the US in 1983 by [[Elektra Records]] and reached number 136 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/breaking-the-chains-mw0000189795/awards |title=Breaking the Chains Billboard Albums |work=[[AllMusic]] |publisher=[[All Media Network]] |accessdate=2015-01-30 }}</ref> The album was considered a flop by the label, which had the intention to drop the band. However, Dokken management convinced Elektra that they could make a more successful album, which materialized in ''[[Tooth and Nail (Dokken album)|Tooth and Nail]]'' in September 1984. ''Breaking the Chains'' title track was named the 62nd greatest hard rock song by [[VH1]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Vh1 Top 100 Hard Rock Songs |publisher=Spreadit Music.org |url=http://music.spreadit.org/vh1-top-100-hard-rock-songs/ |accessdate=February 7, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212180319/http://music.spreadit.org/vh1-top-100-hard-rock-songs/ |archivedate=February 12, 2009 }}</ref> It is featured on the radio station \"V-ROCK\" in the 2006 video game ''[[Grand Theft Auto: Vice City Stories]]''.\n\nIn a discussion with [[George Lynch (musician)|George Lynch]] on January 26, 2011, he mentioned the existence of 500 copies of the Carrere Records ''Breakin' the Chains'' version printed with the Don Dokken moniker, instead of Dokken. This version also featured different album cover art.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://bravewords.com/news/george-lynch-and-don-dokken-trade-barbs-on-dokkens-breaking-the-chains-debut-audio-interviews-streaming |title=GEORGE LYNCH And DON DOKKEN Trade Barbs On DOKKEN's Breaking The Chains Debut; Audio Interviews Streaming |magazine=[[Brave Words & Bloody Knuckles]] |date=5 January 2005 |accessdate=2015-06-29 }}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n\n===1981 Breakin' The Chains (Carrere Records)===\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Side one\n| all_writing     = [[Don Dokken]] and [[George Lynch (musician)|George Lynch]], except where noted\n| title1          = [[Breaking the Chains (song)|Breaking the Chains]]\n| length1         = 3:43\n| title2          = Seven Thunders\n| note2         = Dokken, Lynch, [[Mick Brown (musician)|Mick Brown]]\n| length2         = 3:56\n| title3          = I Can't See You\n| note3         = Dokken, [[Juan Croucier]]\n| length3         = 3:12\n| title4          = In the Middle\n| length4         = 3:44\n| title5          = We're Illegal\n| note5         = Dokken, Lynch, Croucier\n| length5         = 3:39\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Side two\n| title6          = Paris \n| length6         = 3:46\n| title7          = Stick to Your Guns\n| length7         = 3:25\n| title8          = Young Girls\n| length8         = 3:14\n| title9          = Felony\n| length9         = 3:25\n| title10         = Nightrider\n| note10        = Dokken, Lynch, Brown\n| length10        = 3:14\n| total_length    = 35:01\n}}\n\n===1983 Breaking The Chains (Elektra Records)===\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Side one\n| title1          = Breaking the Chains\n| length1         = 3:43\n| title2          = In the Middle\n| length2         = 3:43\n| title3          = Felony\n| length3         = 3:08\n| title4          = I Can't See You\n| note4         = Dokken, [[Juan Croucier]]\n| length4         = 3:12\n| title5          = Live to Rock (Rock to Live)\n| note5         = Dokken, Lynch, Croucier\n| length5         = 3:39\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Side two\n| title6          = Nightrider\n| note6         = Dokken, Lynch, [[Mick Brown (musician)|Mick Brown]]\n| length6         = 3:13\n| title7          = Seven Thunders\n| note7         = Dokken, Lynch, Brown\n| length7         = 3:55\n| title8          = Young Girls\n| length8         = 3:14\n| title9          = Stick to Your Guns\n| length9         = 3:25\n| title10         = Paris Is Burning\n| note10          = live in Berlin, December 1982\n| length10        = 5:07\n| total_length    = 36:24\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n\n===Band members===\n===1981 Breakin' The Chains (Carrere Records)===\n*[[Don Dokken]] \u2013 [[lead vocalist|lead vocals]], [[rhythm guitar]], lead guitar\n*[[George Lynch (musician)|George Lynch]] \u2013 [[lead guitar]]\n*[[Mick Brown (musician)|\"Wild\" Mick Brown]] \u2013 [[drum kit|drums]]\n*[[Juan Croucier]] \u2013 [[bassline|bass]], [[backing vocalist|background vocals, co-lead vocals on 'We're Illegal']]\n\n===1983 Breaking The Chains (Elektra Records)===\n*[[Don Dokken]] \u2013 [[lead vocalist|lead vocals]], [[rhythm guitar]], lead guitar\n*[[George Lynch (musician)|George Lynch]] \u2013 [[lead guitar]]\n*[[Mick Brown (musician)|\"Wild\" Mick Brown]] \u2013 [[drum kit|drums]]\n*[[Juan Croucier]] \u2013 [[bassline|bass]], [[backing vocalist|background vocals]]\n\n===Additional Musicians===\n*[[Peter Baltes]] - bass (only on 1981 version)\n*[[Tom Croucier]] - bass (only on 1981 version)\n\n===Production===\n*[[Michael Wagener]] \u2013 [[record producer|production]], [[audio engineer|engineering]], [[mixing engineer|mixing]]\n*Wyn Davis \u2013 mixing\n*[[Joe Gastwirt]] \u2013 [[mastering engineer|mastering]]\n\n==Notes==\n\nOn the original ''Breakin' The Chains'' Carrere version, released as Don Dokken, several song titles are misspelled on the back cover.  Namely \"I Can't See You\" (\"I Can See You\"), \"Stick To Your Guns\" (\"Still To Your Guns\"), and \"Young Girls\" (\"Young Girl\"). On the French Carrere vinyl release, the songs are spelled correctly, but Lynch's name is misspelled as \u201cGeorges Lynch\u201d.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Dokken}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Breaking The Chains (Dokken Album)}}\n[[Category:1981 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Michael Wagener]]\n[[Category:Dokken albums]]\n[[Category:Elektra Records albums]]\n[[Category:Carrere Records albums]]\n", "name_user": "BRUYLE97", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breaking_the_Chains_(album)"}
